00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:49.060
and dynamism to the library

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:51.860
and that she's only been
here two years, a little less

00:02:51.860 --> 00:02:53.160
than two years and many

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:55.190
of us are excited to
be a part of that.

00:02:55.190 --> 00:02:58.020
As for the Kluge Center
itself under Dr. Hayden,

00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:00.130
the center had re-centered
on its original mission

00:03:00.130 --> 00:03:03.450
to be a bridge between
scholarship on the one hand

00:03:03.450 --> 00:03:06.450
and policymakers and
interested public on the other.

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:10.560
Tonight's event exemplifies
that purpose.

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:14.070
Senator Inouye was a larger than
life figure here in Washington

00:03:14.070 --> 00:03:16.710
and in his home state of Hawaii.

00:03:16.710 --> 00:03:19.130
As a young man, after
the ban was lifted

00:03:19.130 --> 00:03:21.520
on Japanese American
serving their country,

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:24.070
he enlisted in the Army
and served in a unit

00:03:24.070 --> 00:03:26.440
of Japanese American
soldiers who fought

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:30.990
with extraordinary gallantry
in Italy, France, and Germany.

00:03:30.990 --> 00:03:36.920
On October 21, 1945, in the
war's final weeks in Europe,

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:38.920
he was severely wounded.

00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:42.880
He had just taken out two
German machinegun nests,

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:44.730
he lost his right arm.

00:03:44.730 --> 00:03:47.720
He returned home with a
distinguished service cross,

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:52.200
a bronze star medal, two
purple hearts, 12 other medals

00:03:52.200 --> 00:03:56.290
and citations, and not
incidentally a commitment

00:03:56.290 --> 00:03:59.890
to bipartisanship that may
have stemmed from the long,

00:03:59.890 --> 00:04:02.460
lifelong friendship he
formed in an army hospital

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:05.630
with another wounded veteran,
the future Republican Senator,

00:04:05.630 --> 00:04:06.930
Vice-Presidential candidate

00:04:06.930 --> 00:04:10.730
and Presidential
candidate, Kansas's Bob Dole.

00:04:10.730 --> 00:04:12.580
After coming home and
finishing law school,

00:04:12.580 --> 00:04:16.660
Mr. Inouye became Hawaii's
first representative in 1959

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:19.230
which was the year
Hawaii became a state.

00:04:19.230 --> 00:04:21.760
Three years later, he
was elected Senator,

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:25.130
part of freshman class
inspired by President Kennedy,

00:04:25.130 --> 00:04:28.760
which included President
Kennedy's brother Edward.

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:31.310
Senator Inouye served for
nearly a half a century

00:04:31.310 --> 00:04:33.570
in the senate leaving
a rich legacy

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:36.840
that includes the National
Museum of the Native-American,

00:04:36.840 --> 00:04:39.580
prominent service on the Senate
Watergate Committee, as well as,

00:04:39.580 --> 00:04:42.560
on the Iran Contra
Committee and, of course,

00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:45.320
on the Senate Appropriations
Committee which he chaired

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:47.830
in the last several
years of his career.

00:04:47.830 --> 00:04:51.640
He was awarded the Congressional
Medal of Honor in 2000

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:53.670
for his military service.

00:04:53.670 --> 00:04:54.970
After his death,

00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:57.170
he was posthumously awarded
the Presidential Medal

00:04:57.170 --> 00:04:59.510
of Freedom becoming
the first senator

00:04:59.510 --> 00:05:02.680
to receive both of those awards.

00:05:02.680 --> 00:05:05.820
Tonight, the John W. Kluge
Center at the library

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:08.860
and the Daniel K. Inouye
Institute present the 4th

00:05:08.860 --> 00:05:11.250
in a 5-year distinguished
lecture series

00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:14.950
to commemorate Senator Inouye's
commitment to bipartisanship,

00:05:14.950 --> 00:05:18.910
moral courage, public
service, and civic engagement.

00:05:18.910 --> 00:05:21.330
I would now like to
introduce our distinguished

00:05:21.330 --> 00:05:22.630
panelists tonight.

00:05:22.630 --> 00:05:25.910
First, E.J. Dionne who
writes about politics

00:05:25.910 --> 00:05:28.140
in a twice weekly column
for the Washington Post

00:05:28.140 --> 00:05:31.720
where he's worked since 1990,
he's also a government professor

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:34.630
at Georgetown, a visiting
professor at Harvard

00:05:34.630 --> 00:05:37.100
and a senior fellow at
the Brookings Institution.

00:05:37.100 --> 00:05:39.580
He's the sole author of 7 books.

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:43.750
Most recently, "Why the Right
Went Wrong; Conservatism

00:05:43.750 --> 00:05:47.260
from Goldwater to the
Tea Party and Beyond."

00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:50.140
He made his name as a major
political intellectual

00:05:50.140 --> 00:05:51.440
with the publication of

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:55.080
"Why Americans Hate
Politics" in 1991.

00:05:55.080 --> 00:05:57.600
It's not a new thing.

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:00.240
Ross Douthat joined the New
York Times as an op-ed columnist

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:04.110
in April 2009, previously
he had been senior editor

00:06:04.110 --> 00:06:05.410
at the Atlantic.

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:08.020
He is the author of 4
books including this year,

00:06:08.020 --> 00:06:10.810
"To Change the Church;
Pope Francis and the Future

00:06:10.810 --> 00:06:14.220
of Catholicism", as well
as, "Grand New Party;

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:16.790
How Republicans can
Win the Working Class

00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:19.250
and Save the American Dream."

00:06:19.250 --> 00:06:22.030
Our conversation will be
moderated by Ann Compton,

00:06:22.030 --> 00:06:24.950
former ABC News White
House correspondent.

00:06:24.950 --> 00:06:27.970
Ann joined ABC News in 1973.

00:06:27.970 --> 00:06:29.390
She covered 7 presidents.

00:06:29.390 --> 00:06:32.690
She's traveled around the
globe and through all 50 states

00:06:32.690 --> 00:06:34.900
with the presidents,
their vice-presidents,

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:36.520
as well as, first ladies.

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:39.010
We are delighted that
she can be with us.

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:41.770
After the conversation,
we will allot some time

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:43.740
for audience questions,
that would be

00:06:43.740 --> 00:06:46.620
after some prerecorded
questions from students

00:06:46.620 --> 00:06:49.340
at the University
of Hawaii campuses.

00:06:49.340 --> 00:06:52.280
Please join me in welcoming
our distinguished panelists

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:54.510
to the stage.

