00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:18.340
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Good evening.

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:19.640
Thank you.

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:23.330
Aloha to the students who are
watching and to all of you

00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:27.200
who have come tonight to talk
about the American dream.

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:32.600
It probably goes back
to, we hold these truths

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:36.880
to be self-evident "All men are
created equal, life, liberty

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:38.350
and the pursuit of happiness."

00:07:38.350 --> 00:07:41.660
But where is the
American dream today?

00:07:41.660 --> 00:07:47.040
Is there some; can there be such
a thing in a world as diverse

00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:50.500
and deeply divided as
our times as these?

00:07:50.500 --> 00:07:54.130
Senator Dan Inouye lived
the American dream.

00:07:54.130 --> 00:07:58.920
In fact, he bled for it
as President Obama said

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:01.710
in his eulogy when
the senator died.

00:08:01.710 --> 00:08:04.750
Ross I'm going to
start with you.

00:08:04.750 --> 00:08:06.910
You wrote recently about
the American dream,

00:08:06.910 --> 00:08:09.470
you said "It ain't
in California."

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:12.760
&gt;&gt; Ross Douthat:
But possibly Hawaii.

00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:18.750
Right, well that, that
column was about, you know,

00:08:18.750 --> 00:08:20.720
in certain ways I would
say that the State

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:23.960
of California has
become especially perhaps

00:08:23.960 --> 00:08:28.320
in the Presidency of Donald
Trump, a kind of idealized view

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:31.320
of America's political
future for some liberals

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:33.780
and progressives and
democrats in the sense

00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:35.840
that in California
you have a situation

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:39.220
where the Republican
Party as nationally

00:08:39.220 --> 00:08:40.520
as pretty dysfunctional,

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:44.650
but unlike nationally is
pretty much irrelevant as well.

00:08:44.650 --> 00:08:47.790
And in that sense,
California, you know,

00:08:47.790 --> 00:08:51.630
and therefore California is
sort of not only as always sort

00:08:51.630 --> 00:08:54.490
of on the cutting edge of,
you know, new technology

00:08:54.490 --> 00:08:57.340
in Silicon Valley and the
movie industry and so on,

00:08:57.340 --> 00:09:00.240
but is also seen as being
kind of on the cutting edge

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:04.630
of where progressive politics
could hope to be if the darkness

00:09:04.630 --> 00:09:06.240
of the Trump era should pass

00:09:06.240 --> 00:09:09.070
and the emerging democratic
majority should finally emerge.

00:09:09.070 --> 00:09:13.170
And so, the column that I wrote
was basically saying that,

00:09:13.170 --> 00:09:16.830
you know, while that might be
true if you look at the sort

00:09:16.830 --> 00:09:20.540
of sociological landscape of
California, if you look at sort

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:25.720
of the social structure that has
emerged there, it doesn't look

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:29.090
at all what, like what I
think many progressives,

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:32.340
E.J. probably included,
would argue is the essence

00:09:32.340 --> 00:09:34.560
of the American dream and we,
I mean we could sort of go back

00:09:34.560 --> 00:09:36.190
and forth on what
that essence is,

00:09:36.190 --> 00:09:38.750
but I think most people would
say that it has something to do

00:09:38.750 --> 00:09:41.820
with a mix of kind of, you know,

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:46.150
a sort of strong
economically stable middle-class

00:09:46.150 --> 00:09:49.550
and various forms of
sort of social equality

00:09:49.550 --> 00:09:53.140
and upward mobility that sort
of intersect in different ways.

00:09:53.140 --> 00:09:56.510
And the society that
California has even

00:09:56.510 --> 00:10:00.800
under progressive governance is
a much more stratified society

00:10:00.800 --> 00:10:05.480
in which for various complicated
reasons of public policy

00:10:05.480 --> 00:10:07.840
and sort of overall
macro trends,

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:11.550
the middle-class has
basically been priced out

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:15.120
and so you have an
extremely wealthy upper-class

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:18.780
that has sort of entrenched
its privileges in various ways

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:21.840
through land use
regulations and restrictions

00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:23.820
on building and everything else.

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:27.440
And then you have an
increasingly immigrant-base

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:29.830
working-class that
sort of serves as sort

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:33.120
of the service sector for that
economy and you have very little

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:36.540
in between and you have, once
you control for cost of living,

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:39.110
extremely high child
poverty rates,

00:10:39.110 --> 00:10:41.200
extremely high racial
gaps, you know,

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:44.300
again whatever else the American
dream means; it has something

00:10:44.300 --> 00:10:47.070
to with the equality of
the races and the quality

00:10:47.070 --> 00:10:49.340
of opportunity and so on.

00:10:49.340 --> 00:10:52.160
And so, the takeaway from
the column I guess was

00:10:52.160 --> 00:10:54.430
that if this is the future

00:10:54.430 --> 00:10:55.980
and if this is particularly
the future

00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:58.950
that progressives are hoping
to build after the age

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:01.090
of Donald Trump should pass,

00:11:01.090 --> 00:11:03.280
then there's still
considerable work to be done

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:08.240
if that future is going to sort
of dovetail with what, again,

00:11:08.240 --> 00:11:09.990
I think traditionally
Americans have sort

00:11:09.990 --> 00:11:13.880
of imagined the American
dream to be and to just

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:16.680
to personalize it a tiny
bit as I did in the column,

00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:19.040
I'm from the East Coast,
but I was actually born

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:22.690
in San Francisco in 1979.

00:11:22.690 --> 00:11:25.350
And I was born there
because my father was

00:11:25.350 --> 00:11:29.680
from southern California and
he grew up in Santa Monica

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:34.160
in a period when that was a
kind of middle-class paradise.

00:11:34.160 --> 00:11:37.960
His dad was a pretty
unsuccessful small businessman,

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:39.690
I think it's fair to say.

00:11:39.690 --> 00:11:44.570
He ran a bicycle shop badly and
had various sort of salesmany

00:11:44.570 --> 00:11:50.200
"Willy" Lomanish jobs
and my grandmother sort

00:11:50.200 --> 00:11:51.610
of held the house
together, but they were

00:11:51.610 --> 00:11:54.430
in no way what you would
consider sort of a, you know,

00:11:54.430 --> 00:11:56.330
a major American successes.

00:11:56.330 --> 00:12:01.520
They were sort of slightly below
the middle-class, and yet they,

00:12:01.520 --> 00:12:05.740
you know, owned a small
sort of mission style home

00:12:05.740 --> 00:12:08.480
in a neighborhood that was
close to the ocean and felt

00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:11.620
like an earthly paradise and
were surrounded by people

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:14.480
with sort of similar
means and aspirations.

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:16.730
And, you know, there
were all kinds

00:12:16.730 --> 00:12:20.390
of sort inevitable reasons
why that couldn't last,

00:12:20.390 --> 00:12:22.700
but it's still notable that it
didn't last and if you go back

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:25.620
to Santa Monica now, all
those houses like the one

00:12:25.620 --> 00:12:28.360
where my dad grew up have
been torn down to make way

00:12:28.360 --> 00:12:32.120
for structures that are 2 or
3 times too large for the lots

00:12:32.120 --> 00:12:35.320
that they sit on and all
cost 4 or 5 million dollars

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:37.720
and that world is gone.

00:12:37.720 --> 00:12:40.870
And, you know, it was a
racially segregated world,

00:12:40.870 --> 00:12:42.780
it was stratified in
all kinds of other ways.

00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:45.330
There are all kinds of reasons
why it's never coming back,

00:12:45.330 --> 00:12:48.980
but it's still notable that it
existed and then disappeared

00:12:48.980 --> 00:12:50.950
and its disappearance is one

00:12:50.950 --> 00:12:53.680
of the realities I
think underlying some

00:12:53.680 --> 00:12:56.500
of our present political
discontents.

00:12:56.500 --> 00:13:01.120
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: E.J., is the
American dream even possible

00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:05.960
in our society, in a political
society that's as deviant

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:09.100
as Washington is now,
as this country is now?

