00:15:34.150 --> 00:15:37.920
You know, the, I've
thought a lot this topic

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:40.480
in the last few weeks
thinking, you know,

00:15:40.480 --> 00:15:44.980
about the event tonight and the
American dream is a really vexed

00:15:44.980 --> 00:15:50.440
idea that, you know, it can be
seen as a kind of romantic view

00:15:50.440 --> 00:15:53.910
of what opportunity is like
in America given the groups

00:15:53.910 --> 00:15:56.540
over our history who have
been excluded from it,

00:15:56.540 --> 00:16:00.960
but the other side of it
and it may be most powerful

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:05.320
when it's used as a call upon us
to make our country what it not;

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:09.090
what it isn't yet,
but ought to be.

00:16:09.090 --> 00:16:13.750
And two, sort of two uses
like that came to mind;

00:16:13.750 --> 00:16:18.050
one was of course Martin Luther
King's "I Have a Dream" speech

00:16:18.050 --> 00:16:21.020
and he was very explicit
in saying

00:16:21.020 --> 00:16:25.730
"It is a dream deeply rooted
in the American dream."

00:16:25.730 --> 00:16:27.500
And as you suggested
at the beginning,

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:30.040
he too invoked the Declaration.

00:16:30.040 --> 00:16:33.460
I have a dream that one day this
nation will rise up and live

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:36.670
out the true meaning of its
creed we hold these truths

00:16:36.670 --> 00:16:40.160
to be self-evident that
all men are created equal.

00:16:40.160 --> 00:16:43.390
But it can also be
used as a critique.

00:16:43.390 --> 00:16:47.600
Many of you know probably
Langston Hughes' most famous

00:16:47.600 --> 00:16:52.450
poem, "What happens to a
dream deferred does it dry

00:16:52.450 --> 00:16:55.680
up like a raisin in the sun?"

00:16:55.680 --> 00:17:00.200
And what I had forgotten is
how that poem ends which is

00:17:00.200 --> 00:17:03.070
"What Happens to a Dream
Deferred" the last line

00:17:03.070 --> 00:17:06.020
of the poem is, "Or
does it explode?"

00:17:06.020 --> 00:17:10.330
And it's just sort of a reminder
of what can happen when we hold

00:17:10.330 --> 00:17:15.000
up these ideals and then
don't live up to them.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.650
I was trying to figure out
what is a definition of this?

00:17:17.650 --> 00:17:24.050
And I think one take is that
hard work leads to success.

00:17:24.050 --> 00:17:27.540
That's one kind of definition
of the American dream.

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:32.150
The other is that the next
generation will do better

00:17:32.150 --> 00:17:35.600
than the previous generation.

00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:38.800
Those are sort of vexed now.

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:43.450
We still believe, we're
still optimists even

00:17:43.450 --> 00:17:45.580
after everything
we've gone through;

00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:48.950
61% of our population
according Gallup believes

00:17:48.950 --> 00:17:52.280
that young people will live
better than their parents,

00:17:52.280 --> 00:17:56.650
but there has been a decline in
some of these number, you know,

00:17:56.650 --> 00:17:59.280
in at the right at the
turn of the millennium,

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:03.830
74% of us believe that people
who work hard can get ahead

00:18:03.830 --> 00:18:08.300
and that fell to 58% at
the end of the recession.

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:11.710
And to go to just briefly to
your point, can we achieve this

00:18:11.710 --> 00:18:13.390
in a country so divided?

00:18:13.390 --> 00:18:17.080
It strikes me that we
will have trouble sort

00:18:17.080 --> 00:18:21.110
of creating public policy
that might move us forward

00:18:21.110 --> 00:18:23.500
because we are so
deadlocked about what

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:25.840
that policy should
be, but even our view

00:18:25.840 --> 00:18:28.730
of the American dream is
now shaped by partisanship.

00:18:28.730 --> 00:18:34.530
The optimism that people had
in that Gallup survey when up

00:18:34.530 --> 00:18:37.780
because so many republicans
switched from negative

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:41.390
to positive after President
Obama was out of office.

00:18:41.390 --> 00:18:44.880
That's on the one side, and
the other side there was a;

00:18:44.880 --> 00:18:46.870
I was looking at a
study of millennials,

00:18:46.870 --> 00:18:50.140
at the end of the Obama years
African-American millennials

00:18:50.140 --> 00:18:53.970
were much more optimistic, were
much more likely to believe

00:18:53.970 --> 00:18:57.370
in the American dream than
White millennials were.

00:18:57.370 --> 00:19:02.990
So, it's our view of this has
shaped partly by politics,

00:19:02.990 --> 00:19:07.870
partly by race, partly by
where we sit in this society.

