00:20:20.330 --> 00:20:22.650
But I, I mean, I think
generally, You know,

00:20:22.650 --> 00:20:26.030
there's no question that over
the last 40 years on this sort

00:20:26.030 --> 00:20:28.270
of "are you better off
than you parents" question,

00:20:28.270 --> 00:20:32.020
the country has gone through
a long period of stagnation.

00:20:32.020 --> 00:20:35.880
Tyler Cowen who, you know,
E.J. knows well is an economist

00:20:35.880 --> 00:20:38.400
at George Mason and wrote a book
called "The Great Stagnation",

00:20:38.400 --> 00:20:41.220
basically sort of
describing this long period

00:20:41.220 --> 00:20:44.770
where the median income which
is, you know, as good a way

00:20:44.770 --> 00:20:47.570
of sort of measuring you
know the sort of heart

00:20:47.570 --> 00:20:49.260
of American life as any,

00:20:49.260 --> 00:20:53.010
the median income basically got
stuck and so it wasn't a period

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:55.490
of collapse, it wasn't the
Great Depression, you know,

00:20:55.490 --> 00:20:59.770
we slowly we've had obviously
a severe recession recently.

00:20:59.770 --> 00:21:02.930
We've slowly climbed back from,
but basically it's a story

00:21:02.930 --> 00:21:06.380
of a society where the economy
for most people seems kind

00:21:06.380 --> 00:21:10.630
of stuck and where you aren't
sort of, you're doing okay,

00:21:10.630 --> 00:21:14.230
you're not in poverty, you know,
you have Welfare State Programs

00:21:14.230 --> 00:21:16.620
that sort of stabilize
things during recessions,

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:20.390
but what we had gotten used to
during these wave of expansion

00:21:20.390 --> 00:21:22.590
in the, you know, during
the Industrial Revolution

00:21:22.590 --> 00:21:24.880
and then again in
the post war boom,

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:27.350
just hasn't been
there for most people.

00:21:27.350 --> 00:21:32.150
And over that same period
you've had a kind of hollowing

00:21:32.150 --> 00:21:34.320
out of community
in American life,

00:21:34.320 --> 00:21:37.790
because I think another aspect
of the American dream is,

00:21:37.790 --> 00:21:40.740
you know, if you go back to
sort of the people who came

00:21:40.740 --> 00:21:42.630
to visit America in
the 19th-century,

00:21:42.630 --> 00:21:44.410
Alexis de Tocqueville
most famously,

00:21:44.410 --> 00:21:45.980
and sort of what they remarked

00:21:45.980 --> 00:21:47.600
on about American
life they said,

00:21:47.600 --> 00:21:50.270
well you know you have
a weaker state here

00:21:50.270 --> 00:21:51.820
than you often do in Europe.

00:21:51.820 --> 00:21:53.470
You don't have an
established church.

00:21:53.470 --> 00:21:55.760
You don't have a lot of
the big institutions,

00:21:55.760 --> 00:21:59.200
but you have this incredible
community spirit often rooted

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:02.040
in religion, but also just sort
of rooted in civic engagement

00:22:02.040 --> 00:22:05.640
in other things, you know,
from sort of the, you know,

00:22:05.640 --> 00:22:09.420
New England Town Meeting through
the culture of the Midwest

00:22:09.420 --> 00:22:13.390
and so on, and that has
obviously taken a hit

00:22:13.390 --> 00:22:16.670
over the last couple of
generations and there's a long

00:22:16.670 --> 00:22:20.060
and complicated argument about
how those two things intertwine;

00:22:20.060 --> 00:22:23.680
how is the decline of
marriage rates and the decline

00:22:23.680 --> 00:22:26.900
of church going and the decline
of you know bowling leagues

00:22:26.900 --> 00:22:28.790
and all these things,
how is that related

00:22:28.790 --> 00:22:31.800
to economic stagnation,
how the two fit together?

00:22:31.800 --> 00:22:34.690
But that tangle is the sort of,

00:22:34.690 --> 00:22:37.350
that's the central
policy problem I think.

00:22:37.350 --> 00:22:40.420
It's sort of, you know,
how do you figure out one,

00:22:40.420 --> 00:22:44.060
how to get the economy working
better for most Americans?

00:22:44.060 --> 00:22:47.990
And at the same time, how do
you have a kind of, you know,

00:22:47.990 --> 00:22:52.670
a sort of civic and familial
and religious sort of,

00:22:52.670 --> 00:22:55.420
sort of a knitting back
together of the social fabric?

00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:58.080
And, you know, we have a lot
of evidence from the last 5

00:22:58.080 --> 00:23:01.720
or 10 years that this,
you know, that things,

00:23:01.720 --> 00:23:04.040
things have actually gotten
worse in a lot of respects.

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:06.520
I mean, the opioid
epidemic, you know,

00:23:06.520 --> 00:23:09.360
suicide rates have gone up.

00:23:09.360 --> 00:23:12.430
You know, you have a decline
in American life expectancy

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:15.530
for the first time and
all, that's you know sort

00:23:15.530 --> 00:23:17.770
of concentrated in
particular parts of the country

00:23:17.770 --> 00:23:20.680
and especially to E.J.'s
point, it seems to be a,

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:23.380
there's more sort
of social anime

00:23:23.380 --> 00:23:26.540
and despair among White
Americans than among minorities.

00:23:26.540 --> 00:23:28.430
There's more pessimism
among working,

00:23:28.430 --> 00:23:30.360
in working class White America

00:23:30.360 --> 00:23:33.340
than there is among
Blacks and Hispanics.

00:23:33.340 --> 00:23:36.200
But whatever it is, that's,
that's the policy problem

00:23:36.200 --> 00:23:39.650
and to the extent there's
a solution in, you know,

00:23:39.650 --> 00:23:42.830
I think it lies somewhere
at the intersection

00:23:42.830 --> 00:23:44.170
of the social and economic.

00:23:44.170 --> 00:23:47.240
That we should be looking for
policies that basically say,

00:23:47.240 --> 00:23:50.860
well on the one hand you
probably do need to find ways

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:54.480
to raise wages, get more money
into the hands of the middle

00:23:54.480 --> 00:23:56.480
and the working class,
at the same time,

00:23:56.480 --> 00:23:58.070
you want those policies to sort

00:23:58.070 --> 00:24:02.020
of somehow create a
virtuous cycle with families

00:24:02.020 --> 00:24:06.770
and communities and so on
and not just become the kind

00:24:06.770 --> 00:24:08.200
of things that I
think, for instance,

00:24:08.200 --> 00:24:11.200
a lot of Trump voters sort of
rebelled against the idea that,

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:15.880
well you know, your, I think
the Democratic Party has ended

00:24:15.880 --> 00:24:17.180
up in a position

00:24:17.180 --> 00:24:20.580
where technically its economic
policies are more popular,

00:24:20.580 --> 00:24:23.070
but people don't like the idea

00:24:23.070 --> 00:24:25.140
that well my community
has been hollowed out,

00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:26.950
the jobs are never coming back,

00:24:26.950 --> 00:24:29.110
but at least you
know I have Medicaid.

00:24:29.110 --> 00:24:32.920
They liked more the idea that
Trump was selling of, you know,

00:24:32.920 --> 00:24:34.510
you're going to get the
jobs back, things are going

00:24:34.510 --> 00:24:37.140
to be the way they were
before and I don't think

00:24:37.140 --> 00:24:40.790
that was a completely honest
sales pitch, but it spoke

00:24:40.790 --> 00:24:44.210
to a challenge that I think
both parties haven't been able

00:24:44.210 --> 00:24:49.180
to meet that combined
idea of sort of solid jobs

00:24:49.180 --> 00:24:51.060
and solid civic life
that slipped away

00:24:51.060 --> 00:24:52.360
in big parts of the country.

