democratic dream.

00:28:05.260 --> 00:28:07.620
Which is to say,
that the societies

00:28:07.620 --> 00:28:13.680
that have less inequality tend
to have more social mobility

00:28:13.680 --> 00:28:16.860
and that there, you know, I have
my conservative friends always

00:28:16.860 --> 00:28:19.210
like say I'm not for
equality results,

00:28:19.210 --> 00:28:21.460
but I am for equality
of opportunity.

00:28:21.460 --> 00:28:26.500
But what appears to be the case
is if you're class in incomes,

00:28:26.500 --> 00:28:30.530
your class system and your
income distribution gets too far

00:28:30.530 --> 00:28:33.780
out of whack, you
lose the capacity

00:28:33.780 --> 00:28:36.370
for mass upward mobility.

00:28:36.370 --> 00:28:38.820
So, again, this probably
reflects the difference

00:28:38.820 --> 00:28:40.120
in our political view,

00:28:40.120 --> 00:28:44.480
but I think we need somewhat
more egalitarian public policies

00:28:44.480 --> 00:28:47.420
in order to produce
the degree of mobility

00:28:47.420 --> 00:28:50.430
that the American dream
suggests we ought to have.

