01:19:57.930 --> 01:20:00.080
So, each of you use this as kind

01:20:00.080 --> 01:20:04.380
of your closing argument
for tonight.

01:20:04.380 --> 01:20:07.080
&gt;&gt; Ross Douthat: I mean, I'll
seek common ground and say

01:20:07.080 --> 01:20:12.960
that the public policies we
should seek should be policies

01:20:12.960 --> 01:20:16.670
that seek a little more economic
equality that we have right now,

01:20:16.670 --> 01:20:20.520
but that seek it through by
targeting precisely the areas

01:20:20.520 --> 01:20:21.950
that the questioner
is talking about.

01:20:21.950 --> 01:20:25.270
Basically saying, we're going
to provide a little more support

01:20:25.270 --> 01:20:27.890
for work and a little
more support for family,

01:20:27.890 --> 01:20:31.880
and we're going to reorient the
welfare state so that, you know,

01:20:31.880 --> 01:20:34.030
you have a little more money
when you're raising kids,

01:20:34.030 --> 01:20:37.150
you have a larger earned income
tax credit or something like it.

01:20:37.150 --> 01:20:41.980
If you're working a blue collar
job and it gets you to a place

01:20:41.980 --> 01:20:44.900
that conservatives could support
because you're effectively,

01:20:44.900 --> 01:20:46.950
you know, like the
GI Bill you're sort

01:20:46.950 --> 01:20:50.540
of subsidizing hard work
and childrearing than most,

01:20:50.540 --> 01:20:53.230
you know, the most conservative
things of all, but at this,

01:20:53.230 --> 01:20:54.730
but you're doing it in a way

01:20:54.730 --> 01:20:57.940
that does you know push the
society towards a slightly more

01:20:57.940 --> 01:21:01.280
egalitarian income distribution,
because I think that,

01:21:01.280 --> 01:21:02.580
that is the core question.

01:21:02.580 --> 01:21:05.150
You should be able
to if you work hard,

01:21:05.150 --> 01:21:08.310
you should be able to, you
know, get married, buy a house

01:21:08.310 --> 01:21:10.360
and have a family and not
everybody wants to do that,

01:21:10.360 --> 01:21:13.600
but lots of people do and
when America was working

01:21:13.600 --> 01:21:15.720
at its best lots of
people were able to do that

01:21:15.720 --> 01:21:17.810
and I think that's
a worthwhile goal

01:21:17.810 --> 01:21:20.270
for policymakers today as well.

01:21:20.270 --> 01:21:21.910
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: E.J.

01:21:21.910 --> 01:21:24.960
&gt;&gt; E.J. Dionne: The
idea of getting

01:21:24.960 --> 01:21:29.590
to do what you love is
one of the, in a way one

01:21:29.590 --> 01:21:33.450
of the great privileges of life
because there are so many people

01:21:33.450 --> 01:21:38.500
who are essential to our lives
who are not necessary doing work

01:21:38.500 --> 01:21:41.700
that they love, but work
that they have to do.

01:21:41.700 --> 01:21:44.820
And so, I think the
question is, you know,

01:21:44.820 --> 01:21:47.770
in the first instance
what are the ways

01:21:47.770 --> 01:21:50.080
of increasing the chances
that people will get

01:21:50.080 --> 01:21:53.850
to do what they love and
that probably has to do

01:21:53.850 --> 01:21:57.700
with both access to
education on the one side,

01:21:57.700 --> 01:22:02.050
but also I think a whole lot
more respect than we show

01:22:02.050 --> 01:22:06.880
in our society to work that
does not necessarily require a

01:22:06.880 --> 01:22:09.560
college degree, but
reflects commitment,

01:22:09.560 --> 01:22:11.530
reflects craftsmanship.

01:22:11.530 --> 01:22:15.380
I think that one of the
if you compare our economy

01:22:15.380 --> 01:22:18.120
and our social attitudes
to the Germans I think one

01:22:18.120 --> 01:22:20.190
of the things my friend Ed Luce

01:22:20.190 --> 01:22:22.930
of the Financial Times has
written quite eloquently

01:22:22.930 --> 01:22:30.450
about this that that society has
come to respect the work done

01:22:30.450 --> 01:22:33.420
by those who do not
automatically fall

01:22:33.420 --> 01:22:38.980
into some meritocratic elite
and has rewarded it accordingly.

01:22:38.980 --> 01:22:43.230
And the I'm heartened
to hear Ross

01:22:43.230 --> 01:22:49.630
for his egalitarian
approach and it pains me

01:22:49.630 --> 01:22:53.700
that there are not very many
conservatives these days

01:22:53.700 --> 01:22:57.250
who are willing to embrace
that kind of egalitarianism,

01:22:57.250 --> 01:22:59.590
in a way I think more
conservatives did.

01:22:59.590 --> 01:23:02.370
We look back and think
of Robert Taft as deeply,

01:23:02.370 --> 01:23:05.930
deeply conservative and
yet he was in that era

01:23:05.930 --> 01:23:08.270
of shared commitment created

01:23:08.270 --> 01:23:12.040
by the New Deal and
by World War II.

01:23:12.040 --> 01:23:15.530
He was willing to say that
the market all by itself,

01:23:15.530 --> 01:23:16.830
the wardens of the market all

01:23:16.830 --> 01:23:21.070
by itself will not guarantee
the good life for people.

01:23:21.070 --> 01:23:23.370
And I'd like to see us
have a different kind

01:23:23.370 --> 01:23:26.090
of political debate
where a conservative

01:23:26.090 --> 01:23:29.680
like Ross might correct
me in my hope

01:23:29.680 --> 01:23:32.760
or perhaps I have too much
hope in X government program,

01:23:32.760 --> 01:23:37.200
perhaps I'd be more willing
to tax people than he would,

01:23:37.200 --> 01:23:42.730
but yet we would share
a commitment to the idea

01:23:42.730 --> 01:23:46.990
that you can't make the,
create the American dream

01:23:46.990 --> 01:23:52.160
without individual effort,
but you can't create a society

01:23:52.160 --> 01:23:55.230
in which the American
dream is possible

01:23:55.230 --> 01:23:58.070
without some collective
action, some collective effort

01:23:58.070 --> 01:24:01.520
and a real commitment
to each other

01:24:01.520 --> 01:24:03.610
and not just to ourselves alone.

01:24:03.610 --> 01:24:05.520
&gt;&gt; Ross Douthat: But the
irony it should be said

01:24:05.520 --> 01:24:07.890
since we have both been
in different ways critical

01:24:07.890 --> 01:24:09.720
of the President of the
United States tonight,

01:24:09.720 --> 01:24:12.840
the irony of the Trump era is
that one of the many reasons

01:24:12.840 --> 01:24:16.390
that Donald Trump was elected
president was his particular

01:24:16.390 --> 01:24:17.690
sort of bludgeoning

01:24:17.690 --> 01:24:21.390
and demagogic way he did
provide that kind of vision.

01:24:21.390 --> 01:24:24.630
It was, you know, there isn't
actually necessarily policy

01:24:24.630 --> 01:24:28.680
to back it up, but the Donald
Trump Republican vision was

01:24:28.680 --> 01:24:31.660
closer to what you're
describing than the Paul Ryan,

01:24:31.660 --> 01:24:34.020
Mitt Romney vision
4 years before.

01:24:34.020 --> 01:24:37.370
That's, I think that's
something that the populism

01:24:37.370 --> 01:24:41.920
of Trump is a sort of
crude grasp at that center

01:24:41.920 --> 01:24:43.910
that you're talking about.

01:24:43.910 --> 01:24:45.210
&gt;&gt; E.J. Dionne: Well,

01:24:45.210 --> 01:24:48.420
what I would argue back is
what's particularly insidious

01:24:48.420 --> 01:24:53.210
about what Trump did is
that it carried that promise

01:24:53.210 --> 01:24:58.860
with policies that are actually
antithetical to that promise.

01:24:58.860 --> 01:25:02.830
I always felt, for example,
that when you know progressives

01:25:02.830 --> 01:25:07.390
and even moderates say to a
lot of folks who find at age 50

01:25:07.390 --> 01:25:11.100
that they are not in a job that
provides them with the income

01:25:11.100 --> 01:25:13.230
that they used to have
to support their families

01:25:13.230 --> 01:25:17.370
and live a decent life, and
the typical policy person

01:25:17.370 --> 01:25:20.070
who happens to be a college
educated comes along and says,

01:25:20.070 --> 01:25:22.130
"Would you need more
training and education?"

01:25:22.130 --> 01:25:23.800
And there's truth to that,

01:25:23.800 --> 01:25:26.670
but I think that person has
every right to think what

01:25:26.670 --> 01:25:30.670
that person is telling us is
we got to be more like them

01:25:30.670 --> 01:25:36.310
and it comes off as, as
condescending and not

01:25:36.310 --> 01:25:38.390
in any way genuinely empathic.

01:25:38.390 --> 01:25:40.000
When Trump said, "I'm going

01:25:40.000 --> 01:25:43.150
to bring back those factory
jobs and those coal jobs."

01:25:43.150 --> 01:25:44.600
Of course he wasn't
going to do that.

01:25:44.600 --> 01:25:47.570
I have a strong suspicion that
many of the people who heard

01:25:47.570 --> 01:25:52.690
that and shared know that's
not true, but they had a sense

01:25:52.690 --> 01:25:57.610
from that that he understood
the way they felt better

01:25:57.610 --> 01:26:01.410
than the person who kept talking
about training and education,

01:26:01.410 --> 01:26:04.950
so I during the campaign,

01:26:04.950 --> 01:26:08.880
one of the best nicest
moments I had is I suggested

01:26:08.880 --> 01:26:12.420
that the hat I wanted
to wear would say,

01:26:12.420 --> 01:26:14.520
"Make America Empathetic Again."

01:26:14.520 --> 01:26:18.620
And a very nice person in
the audience came up to me

01:26:18.620 --> 01:26:19.920
and said, "I love that.

01:26:19.920 --> 01:26:21.220
You're going to hear from me."

01:26:21.220 --> 01:26:23.900
And I got this hat
and I got in my mail

01:26:23.900 --> 01:26:25.900
and it was perfect
grappling of the Trump hat,

01:26:25.900 --> 01:26:28.000
but it said "Make
America Empathetic Again."

01:26:28.000 --> 01:26:30.740
And my son said "That's awesome
dad but you can't wear it

01:26:30.740 --> 01:26:35.400
because he did too good a job
and it looks like a Trump hat."

01:26:35.400 --> 01:26:39.500
But I do think that
we are, you know,

01:26:39.500 --> 01:26:41.690
if our country dies it will be

01:26:41.690 --> 01:26:44.670
because of our absolute
inability

01:26:44.670 --> 01:26:50.000
to understand the suffering and
the pain of people unlike us,

01:26:50.000 --> 01:26:56.100
and that the worse kind
of politics is a politics

01:26:56.100 --> 01:27:00.610
that holds one group's pain
against another group's pain

01:27:00.610 --> 01:27:03.430
and that's what we have
to find a remedy for.

01:27:03.430 --> 01:27:08.140
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: The conversation
